SIMPLE: farewell
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Farewell
<hw>Fare`well"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>interj.</pos>
<ety>[<ets>Fare</ets> (thou, you) + <ets>well</ets>.]</ety> <def>Go
well; good-by; adieu; -- originally applied to a person departing, but
by custom now applied both to those who depart and those who remain. It
is often separated by the pronoun; <as>as, <ex>fare</ex> you
<ex>well</ex></as>; and is sometimes used as an expression of separation
only; <as>as, <ex>farewell</ex> the year; <ex>farewell</ex>, ye sweet
groves; that is, I bid you <ex>farewell</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So <qex>farewell</qex> hope, and with hope, <qex>farewell</qex>
fear.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Fare</qex> thee <qex>well</qex>! and if forever,⟦br⟧
Still forever <qex>fare</qex> thee <qex>well</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The primary accent is sometimes placed on the first
syllable, especially in poetry.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Farewell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Farewell
<hw>Fare`well"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A wish
of happiness or welfare at parting; the parting compliment; a good-by;
adieu.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Act of departure; leave-taking; a last look at, or
reference to something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And takes her <qex>farewell</qex> of the glorious sun.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Before I take my <qex>farewell</qex> of the subject.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Farewell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Farewell
<hw>Fare"well`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Parting;
valedictory; final; <as>as, a <ex>farewell</ex> discourse; his
<ex>farewell</ex> bow.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Leans in his spear to take his <qex>farewell</qex> view.</q>
<rj><qau>Tickell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Farewell rock</b></col> <fld>(Mining)</fld>, <cd>the
Millstone grit; -- so called because no coal is found worth working
below this stratum. It is used for hearths of furnaces, having power to
resist intense heat.</cd> <rj><au>Ure.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Farfet</ent>⟦br⟧
